The Arousal Valence Mapping on the labels of the WESAD dataset:

a) Arousal of the emotion: '1' is for high arousal and '0' is for low arousal. 
    wesad['label'] == 0: -1 (not useful as it is not defined) 
    wesad['label'] == 1: 0  (baseline) 
    wesad['label'] == 2: 1  (stress) 
    wesad['label'] == 3: 0  (amusement) 
    wesad['label'] == 4: 1  (meditation) 
    wesad['label'] == 5: -1 (not useful) 
    wesad['label'] == 6: -1 (not useful) 
    wesad['label'] == 7: -1 (not useful) 

b) valence of the emotion: '1' is for positive emotion (high valence) and '0' is for negative|neutral emotion (low valence)
    wesad['label'] == 0: -1 (not useful as it is not defined) 
    wesad['label'] == 1: 0  (baseline) 
    wesad['label'] == 2: 0  (stress) 
    wesad['label'] == 3: 1  (amusement) 
    wesad['label'] == 4: 1  (meditation) 
    wesad['label'] == 5: -1 (not useful) 
    wesad['label'] == 6: -1 (not useful) 
    wesad['label'] == 7: -1 (not useful) 

Link for the Wesad dataset: https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3242969.3242985

Bibtex: Philip Schmidt, Attila Reiss, Robert Duerichen, Claus Marberger, and Kristof Van Laerhoven.
2018. Introducing WESAD, a Multimodal Dataset for Wearable Stress and Affect Detection. In
Proceedings of the 20th ACM International Conference on Multimodal Interaction (ICMI ’18).
Association for Computing Machinery, New York, NY, USA, 400–408. https://doi.org/10.
1145/3242969.3242985
